-font-size:\r\n11.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";=\"\" color:#999999\"=\"\">DK -&nbsp;<i>How to Grow Practically Everything</i>&nbsp;ÃƒÆ’Ã†â€™ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…Â¡ÃƒÆ’Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â© 2010\r\nDorling Kindersley Limited</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\r\n\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:4.5pt;line-height:17.25pt;mso-outline-level:\r\n2;background:white\"><span style=\"font-size:16.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Mulching<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:6.0pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Materials spread on\r\ntop of the ground, usually around plants, are called mulches. They can be\r\npracticalÃƒÆ’Ã†â€™Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â¢ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…Â¡Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â¬ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Âfeeding the soil, suppressing weeds, retaining moisture, or\r\ninsulating roots in winterÃƒÆ’Ã†â€™Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â¢ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…Â¡Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â¬ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Âor mainly decorative, applied for visual effect.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:6.0pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Mulches are applied at\r\ndifferent times depending on their purpose. For example, bark chips are spread\r\nover the soil after planting to suppress weeds. An organic mulch, such as\r\nmanure, garden compost, chipped bark, or cocoa shells, must be laid over moist\r\nsoil, whether in spring, after autumn and winter rains, or after watering.\r\nOrganic mulches help retain moisture but if laid too close to plant stems can\r\ncause them to rot, so keep them at a safe distance. Some mulches, especially\r\nbark, use up nutrients temporarily as they decompose, so before laying them,\r\napply a nitrogen-rich fertilizer, such as fish meal. Lay organic mulches in a\r\nlayer 4in (10cm) deep so they continue to provide cover as they slowly\r\ndecompose and feed the soil. Replenish these mulches every year.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:5.25pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:8.5pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";mso-fareast-font-family:=\"\" \"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#999999\"=\"\">DK -&nbsp;<i>How to Grow Practically\r\nEverything</i>&nbsp;ÃƒÆ’Ã†â€™ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…Â¡ÃƒÆ’Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â© 2010 Dorling Kindersley Limited</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";mso-fareast-font-family:=\"\" \"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:4.5pt;line-height:17.25pt;mso-outline-level:\r\n2;background:white\"><span style=\"font-size:16.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Practical Solutions<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:6.0pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Man-made mulches offer\r\nmany benefits. Weed membrane or landscape fabric is a semipermeable material\r\nthat blocks out light but allows moisture through. Use it on low-maintenance\r\nbeds, or on weed-ridden ground. Lay it before planting and cover with a natural\r\nbark or gravel, or a decorative mulch. Black plastic does not allow moisture\r\nthrough, but it warms the soil and kills off weeds when laid over vegetable\r\nbeds in spring.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:6.0pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Straw insulates the\r\nsoil, and protects tender plants in winter. It is also used to raise crops,\r\nsuch as strawberries and zucchinis, off the ground, reducing fungal and slug\r\nproblems. A think layer of straw will protect the roots of vulnerable plants\r\nfrom frost.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom:6.0pt;line-height:16.5pt;background:\r\nwhite\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#444444\"=\"\">Spread landscape\r\nfabric over the soil prior to planting to prevent weed growth (image 1). Use\r\nstraw to keep strawberries clean and dry (image 2).<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-top:0in;margin-right:15.75pt;margin-bottom:\r\n0in;margin-left:10.5pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:\r\n16.5pt;mso-list:l7 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in;background:white\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Symbol;color:#444444\">ÃƒÆ’Ã†â€™ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…Â¡ÃƒÆ’Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â·<span style=\"font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &acute;Times New Roman&acute;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span><a href=\"http://www.hgtv.com/gardening/feeding-your-plants/page-2.html\"><span style=\"font-size:8.5pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:\" arial\",\"sans-serif\";=\"\" mso-fareast-font-family:\"times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";color:#3