,'Active','2013-12-31 06:03:24','smallCONT-00162Dobir Saheb-er Sangsar..jpg','midCONT-00162Dobir Saheb-er Sangsar..jpg','bigCONT-00162Dobir Saheb-er Sangsar..jpg','USR-000001','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',2),('CONT-00163',NULL,'5 TIPS FOR CLEANING AS YOU GO','','<div><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249);\">One of the biggest keys to keeping your home clean and tidy without spending hours on end with a dust cloth and vacuum is to clean a little bit all the time -- but sometimes that&acute;s easier said than done. Whether you always seem crunched for time or find it easy to get distracted by all the other messes on your way to the cleaning supplies, there are simple tricks to make cleaning as you go a part of your routine that you can stick to, and the results are well worth it.</span></div><div><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249);\"><br></span></div><div><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">1. Keep Cleaning Supplies in Every Room</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Wiping up a mess is never easy if you don&acute;t have the right tools to do it. Keep the proper cleaning supplies that you need to clean that space tucked away in each room of the house. Wiping down the counters or doing a quick clean of the toilet is always easier if you don&acute;t have to leave the room to get what you need. You may need to invest in multiples of the same product, but you won&acute;t regret it.</p></div><div><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">2. Buy a Small Cordless Upright Vacuum</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Lugging out the big vacuum can be a real chore, but if you have a small cordless one that&acute;s easy to grab so you can suck up those crumbs under the table, you&acute;ll be much more likely to do it as soon as you see them hit the floor. Consider getting one for each level of your house, but make them uprights so you don&acute;t have to break your back bending over to reach those crumbs.</p><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\"><br></p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">3. Schedule Your Cleaning Time into Your Routine</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Even if you are cleaning as you go, you need to schedule that into your routine. If you typically plan on 30 minutes for dinner time, plan on 35 minutes instead so you have a few minutes to load the dishwasher, wipe down the counters, and put your ingredients away while the spaghetti sauce finishes simmering. Allotting those few extra minutes will prevent you from feeling rushed and help you stick with the plan.</p><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\"><br></p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">4. Place Baskets for Storing Small Items around the House</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">One of the hardest parts of cleaning on the go is trying to figure out where to put all those little items that pile up around the house. From toys to mail to school supplies, there are always lots of small items that float around from room to room. Placing baskets around the house to catch them makes a big difference in helping them find a home instead of watching them get moved from the table to the counter to the stairs. Just take a minute to toss them into a basket and they&acute;ll be quickly contained and your home will be de-cluttered.</p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">5. Multitask</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Yes, cleaning as you go means multi-tasking, but it can be taken to another level. Instead of just doing the dishes as you finish using them, you can also clean as you go while you are doing non-household related tasks. The next time you&acute;re chatting on the phone, walk around the house and pick up stray toys or laundry that the kids left behind. While watching television, dust those end tables during the commercials. Cleaning as you go is all about doing small tasks in the little spare moments you find in your day so that things stay neat and clean and you don&acute;t have to devote your entire weekend to a deep clean of the house.</p></div>','General','General','','Same','Active','2013-12-31 10:01:39','smallCONT-001635 cleaning.jpg','midCONT-001635 cleaning.jpg','bigCONT-001635 cleaning.jpg','USR-000001','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',1),('CONT-00164',NULL,'10 FUN IDEAS FOR SEASONAL HOME SCENTS','','<span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249);\">Scenting your home for the holidays ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œ from July 4th to Halloween to Christmas ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œ can take the best times of the year to a special place. Making simple simmer scents is simple, and you can reuse the scents up to three times each by storing the liquid in your refrigerator between uses. Another simple idea for home scents for all seasons: Save extras from cooking and from the pantry ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œ like citrus rinds, bits of ginger, herbs and expired juice -- for amazing, inexpensive ways to spice up your fragrances. Just toss them in a sealed bag in the freezer and pull them out to create a cozy mood in your home all year long.</span><div><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249);\"><br></span></div><div><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">10. Cold Weather Scents</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Coming off the holiday season, you&acute;re going to want to keep your home smelling cozy and bright. Try simmering coffee grounds and cinnamon in a low pan or slow cooker for the day. The coffee smells cozy without being overtly ho-ho-holiday, and will cover any smells you&acute;re worried about.</p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">9. Love Scents</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">When it&acute;s still cold outside but your heart is full of love on February 14, set the Valentine&acute;s Day mood with simmering cinnamon sticks and vanilla, or burn a cinnamon spice candle to heat things up. You also can&acute;t go wrong with fresh rose petals for a welcome bouquet with a burst of fragrance.</p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">8. Spring Fling</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Fresh flowers might not be blooming in your garden, but you can pick up hothouse spring blooms in your grocery store or home store. Roses, lilies, and gardenias are some of the most fragrant choices.</p><h2 class=\"slideshow-item-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 5px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: ClarendonTextProRegular, serif; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px;\">7. Spring Scents</h2><p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 9px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Make your home smell of spring by simmering a pot on the stove, filled about 2/3 of the way with water. Add thinly sliced lemons, a few sprigs of rosemary and a splash or two of vanilla or another springy essential oil. Your still-chilly home will smell fresh and light!</p><div class=\"slideshow-item slideoff\" style=\"width: 602px; padding: 10px; margin: 0px 0px 20px; overflow: hidden; opacity: 1; float: left; position: absolute; top: 0px; left: -642px; background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); border-right-width: 1px; border-right-style: solid; border-right-color: rgb(204, 204, 204); border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(204, 204, 204); min-height: 468px; -webkit-transition: left 350ms ease-in; transition: left